    <caption>When images are used from the web, be sure to recognize copyrights and give credit for images when appropriate. (attribution: Used with permission from Microsoft)</caption>
    </figure>
    </section>
    <section id="sect-00005">
    <title>Shapes</title>
    <para id="para-00015">The <term class="no-emphasis" id="term-00009">Shapes</term> drop-down menu is a useful command if you are designing an ad, flyer, newsletter, or other graphic-heavy document. Shapes are graphical symbols, like arrows, rectangles, circles, and lines, that can be formatted in different ways. These can be useful in business documents because they can help call attention to certain topics or data without being as eye-catching as a photograph. For example, you might want to insert an arrow shape in the market trends report to draw attention to a specific item in a graph or chart. Or you might want to use a circle to outline a key part of a table. However, keep in mind the professionalism and visual appeal of the document you are preparing. Shapes might not be appropriate in all situations.</para>
    <para id="para-00016">In <link target-id="fig-00009"/>, you can see the wide range of shapes that you can add to your document. Let’s add an arrow to a table that we might use in the market trends report to highlight an important number in the table. This table contains television sales data for WorldCorp. We will revisit some of this data as we move through the spreadsheet chapters.</para>
    <para id="para-00017">We want to point out the highest quantity sold in the table. To insert an arrow, go to the Insert tab, Illustrations command group, and select Shapes. Select the arrow you want to insert. In this example, the single line arrow (third over from the left) is selected, as shown in the figure. When you select the shape, you will get a black “+” as the cursor. Use that plus sign to insert the shape and to size the shape as you choose.</para>
    <figure id="fig-00009">
    <media alt="The Insert tab is selected on the Ribbon and in the Illustrations command group the Shapes button opens to a pane with categories of various shapes for selection: Recently Used Shapes, Lines, Rectangles, Basic Shapes, Block Arrows, Equation Shapes, and Flowchart. On the table visible in the background, all of the cells are populated with text and numerical data.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OSX_BCA_04_02_SHAPEa.jpg"/>
    </media>
    <caption>There are many shapes for adding emphasis and visual appeal to your documents. (attribution: Used with permission from Microsoft)</caption>
    </figure>
    <para id="para-00018">After you select and insert a shape, the <term class="no-emphasis" id="term-00010">Shape Format</term> tab is added to the Ribbon, as shown in <link target-id="fig-00010"/>. You can change the color of the shape, add visual effects, align the object, use a word wrap, and change the position of the item.</para>
    <figure id="fig-00010" class="scaled-down">
    <media alt="The Shape Format tab is selected on the Ribbon and the following command groups are available: Shape Styles (includes Color, Shape Fill, Shape Outline, and Shape Effects), WordArt Styles (includes Quick Styles, Text Fill, Text Outline, and Text Effects), Text (includes Text Direction, Align Text, and Create Link), Accessibility (includes Alt Text), and Arrange (includes Position, Wrap Text, and Bring Forward). In the table in the document, an arrow is visible outside of the last column and pointing to the number in the cell in the 6th row of the 7th column.">
